article.headline: Shock now 5-8 under new coach Laimbeer

images.caption: Elaine Powell of Detroit drives past Washington's Coco Miller on her way to a 10-point night.

article.linkText: Detroit continues to Shock, beating division-leading Mystics
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Swin Cash had 17 points and eight
rebounds as the Detroit Shock beat the Eastern Conference-leading
Washington Mystics 64-58 on Thursday night.

<photo1>

	   Astou Ndiaye-Diatta added 12 points and 12 rebounds to help the
Shock (5-18) improve to 5-8 since former Pistons player Bill
Laimbeer replaced Greg Williams as head coach.

	   ''We're sending a message to other teams that we're getting
better and we're a team to be reckoned with,'' Laimbeer said.

	   The Shock held a 45-26 rebounding advantage and outscored the
Mystics 24-5 from the free-throw line.

	   Barb Farris and Elaine Powell each had 10 points for Detroit,
and Powell also had six assists.

	   Vicky Bullett led the Mystics (15-8) with 15 points. She scored
seven during a 9-5 run to give her team their biggest lead at
38-29, but Ndiaye-Diatta scored six points and Cash five to spark a
20-7 run that gave the Shock a 49-45 lead with 8:35 left.

	   ''I just think that in the end of the game we just lost
energy,'' Bullett said. ''We just weren't boxing out rebounding. We
gave them second-chance shots, and they took advantage of it.''

	   The Mystics played their ninth consecutive game without All-Star
forward Chamique Holdsclaw, expected to return to the lineup from a
severely sprained left ankle Saturday night against Seattle.

	   ''We really haven't changed much of anything,'' Mystics coach
Marianne Stanley said. ''We just needed other people to step up and
they didn't. We are asking people to step up in her absence,
normally we do that, today we didn't.''

	   Stacey Dales-Schuman and Coco Miller each scored 11 points for
the Mystics.
